"Bondiou-Clergerie A., Lalande P., Roux F.","""ORAGES"": A dedicated sensor for detection, localisation and fine analysis of lightning flashes from space",2004,"Acta Astronautica","55","3-9",,"245","254",,,10.1016/j.actaastro.2004.05.050,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-3843056764&partnerID=40&md5=83d9b54874093672ba92223f4750aa4f","Onera, 29 Av. de la division Leclerc, 92322 Chatillon, France; Laboratoire d'Aérologie, 14 Av. Edouard Belin, 31400 Toulouse, France","Bondiou-Clergerie, A., Onera, 29 Av. de la division Leclerc, 92322 Chatillon, France; Lalande, P., Onera, 29 Av. de la division Leclerc, 92322 Chatillon, France; Roux, F., Laboratoire d'Aérologie, 14 Av. Edouard Belin, 31400 Toulouse, France","According to mission parameters, space-based lightning sensors enable detailed analysis of mesoscale convective systems and large scale atmospheric perturbations (e.g. intertropical convergence zone, monsoon regions, tropical cyclones) and/or statistical studies of the global parameters related to electrical activity on a large spatial and temporal scale. Measurement of spatial distribution and frequency of atmospheric discharges, correlated with meteorological satellites observations, gives the opportunity to have a more precise knowledge of convective systems, to identify the more active regions, to characterise their life cycle and to establish a geographical and seasonal climatology of thunderstorms. Additionally, the global analysis of the electrical activity of thunderstorms could be a diagnosis element of global warming or a quantitative basis for the compared evaluation of natural and anthropic production of nitrogen oxides. Within the CNES microsatellite program, the ORAGES mission was proposed in order to carry out lightning detection, localisation and characterisation based upon the interferometric analysis of their VHF radiation. The present paper describes the different components of the instrument (antenna network, receiver and data-processing system) and presents an evaluation of its performances. © 2003 International Astronautical Federation. Published by Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.",,"Climatology; Demodulation; Global warming; Interferometry; Lightning; Nitrogen oxides; Observatories; Parameter estimation; Perturbation techniques; Space flight; Statistical methods; Storms; Thunderstorms; Weather satellites; Atmospheric discharges; Lightning flashes; Localization; Microsatellite program; Sensors",,,,,,"Lhermitte, R., Williams, E.R., (1983) Reviews of Geophysics, 21, pp. 984-992; Saunders, C.P.R., Keith, W.D., Mitzeva, R.P., (1991) Journal of Geophysical Research, 96, pp. 11007-11017; Chèze, J.L., Sauvageot, H., (1997) Journal of Geophysical Research, 102, p. 1707; Toracinta, E.R., Zipser, E.J., (2001) Journal of Applied Meteorology, 40, pp. 983-1002; Toracinta, E.R., Cecil, D., Zipser, E.J., Nesbitt, S.W., (2002) Monthly Weather Reviews, 130, pp. 802-824; Price, C., (1993) Geophysical Research Letters, 20, pp. 1363-1366; Williams, E.R., (1994) Monthly Weather Reviews, 122, pp. 1917-1929; Price, C., (2000) Nature, 206, pp. 290-293","Bondiou-Clergerie, A.; Onera, 29 Av. de la division Leclerc, 92322 Chatillon, France; email: bondiou@onera.fr",,,,,,,,00945765,,AASTC,,"English","Acta Astronaut",Conference Paper,Scopus,2-s2.0-3843056764
